  The Maturity Gate: What's Failing and Why
                                                                                                                                                            
  The Track A maturity gate determines when the model can advance to the next training phase. Three metrics are failing at step 10000. None of them indicate
   bugs — they indicate the model is exactly where a 1.5B model should be at 10,000 steps of early distillation.                                            
                  
  1. prediction_error_health: 37.04 (threshold: 2.0)                                                                                                        
                  
  This is the most fundamental failing metric. It measures the model's raw epistemic uncertainty — how surprised it is by the next token, averaged over the 
  training window. At 37, the model is still very uncertain about next-token predictions. The threshold of 2.0 represents a model that has genuinely
  internalized language patterns.                                                                                                                           
                  
  This is not a bug. 10,000 steps into distillation from a 7B teacher, a 1.5B model with 36 layers including novel Mamba-3 blocks, full Life Equation       
  infrastructure, and no pretraining to fall back on will have high prediction error. The slow decline from ~37.6 to ~37.0 confirms learning is happening.
  The prediction error will fall dramatically once distillation gets into full stride — but that's a longer-horizon event, likely at 50,000–100,000+ steps. 
                  
  2. memory_discipline: 22.8% (threshold: 15%)                                                                                                              
   
  The controller's INSPECT_MEMORY action is being selected too often. The model is writing to episodic memory on 22.8% of steps, vs. the 15% maximum we     
  want. High write rates mean the episodic buffer fills with noisy, low-quality memories (the controller can't yet tell which moments are worth storing).
                                                                                                                                                            
  This is actively fixed and will be corrected on the next run. We deployed a -1.0 logit bias against INSPECT_MEMORY before the controller's softmax. This  
  makes the action approximately 2.7× harder to select, which should drop the write rate from 22.8% to approximately 8–10% — well inside the 15% target.
                                                                                                                                                            
  3. controller_reliability: 0.422 (threshold: 0.60)

  This metric measures recall: what fraction of "genuine distress" events (steps where epistemic uncertainty exceeds the threshold) did the controller      
  correctly respond to with a non-CONTINUE action?
                                                                                                                                                            
  The problem is circular right now: because prediction_error_health is 37+ and the threshold is 0.5, every single step registers as a "genuine distress"   
  event. The denominator is the entire training set. So controller recall = non-CONTINUE action rate = ~42%. To pass, we'd need the controller firing on
  >60% of all steps — which is actually undesirable behavior (that means the controller is panicking constantly).                                           
                  
  This is a self-resolving metric. Once L_pred drops, the "genuine distress" denominator shrinks to only the truly abnormal steps. At that point, the same  
  controller behavior that's "42% recall" today will look like "recall = 0.9+" because it'll be measured only against the rare high-uncertainty steps.
                                                                                                                                                            
